summary:
Secretory IgA provides critical local protection against staphylococcal exfoliatives toxins at epidermal surfaces such as the skin. Infants have an underdeveloped immune response lacking sufficient levels of these protective antibodies, making them particularly vulnerable to conditions like streptoccocal scalded-skin syndrome (SSc).  

\boxed{C}

The summary focuses only on clinically significant aspects related to infant susceptibility and pathogen interaction—specifically highlighting how deficient secretory IgA leads directly to increased risk from toxic effects of group A Streptococcus strains affecting cutaneous integrity during infancy. This explains why young children present with severe rashes linked to bacterial toxins without requiring additional complications beyond impaired barrier defenses.

